The course introduces the students to the main theories in normative ethics. First, we introduce theories of the good life: hedonism, desire-satisfaction, objective list theories. Second, we introduce theories of what is specifically morally good or bad, right or wrong: utilitarianism, Kantian ethics, pluralism, virtue ethics. The course is based on regular homework, meetings in seminars, and a final essay.Objectives/eesmärkid:  The course aims to: 1) provide an overview of the main problems, concepts and theories in ethics, 2) introduce the students to classical and modern text of ethics, 3) develop the students' ability to argue, analyze and discuss, both in written and oral form, 4) support personal values clarificationLearning outcomes/õpiväljund:  By the end of the course the students understand the meaning of the central concepts in ethics, can use those concepts, have an overview of the main moral theories, can characterize them and know their strengths and weaknesses as well as subdivisions. They also know some central ethical text and can, on a general level, follow the logical structure and details of argumentation. They are able to discuss and analyze ethical texts and arguments on a basic level and are able to take a justified position on practical ethical questions.
